Since $x^{1/3}$ is an odd function and $\cos(x)$ is an even function, we
know that their product is an odd function. More directly, notice that
if

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(x) = x^{1/3}\cos(x)\, dx
\end{align*}

then

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(-x) = (-x)^{1/3}\cos(-x) = -x^{1/3}\cos(x) = -f(x)
\end{align*}

and so the function is odd. As the interval of integration is symmetric,
we have that

\begin{align*}
\int_{-2012}^{2012}x^{1/3}\cos(x)\, dx = 0.
\end{align*}
